The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 TAXING TIMES 

 direct taxes

 No change in rates of personal income-tax or 

 corporate income-tax

 No new taxes being imposed

 One-by-six scheme abolished

 Bank deposits of not less than 5 years brought under Section 80C

 Anonymous or pseudonymous donations to wholly charitable institutions will be taxed at the highest 

 marginal rate

 Banking cash transaction tax stays

 Fringe Benefit tax

 Changes made:

 Value the benefit of tour and travel at 5 per cent instead of 20 per cent;

 Value the benefit of hospitality and use of hotel boarding and lodging facilities for airline companies and shipping industry at 5 per cent instead of 20 per cent;

 Exclude expenses on free samples of medicines and medical equipment distributed to doctors; 

 Exclude expenses incurred on brand ambassadors and celebrity endorsements

 Shares amp; Dividends

 Securities transaction tax increased by 25 per cent

 Open-ended and close-ended equity-oriented schemes 

 to be treated on a par for exemption from dividend distribution tax

 MAT rate raised to 10 per cent 

 indirect taxes

 Excise

 Duty on small cars down to 16 per cent. A small car will mean a car of length not exceeding 4,000 mm and with engine capacity not exceeding 1500 cc for diesel and not over 1200 cc for petrol 

 Aerated drinks to attract 16 per cent duty

 Duty on all man-made fibre yarn and filament yarn cut to 8 per cent from 16 per cent

 An 8 per cent duty on packaged software 

 DVD drives, flash drives and combo drives exempted

 Condensed milk, ice cream, pasta, yeast exempted; duty on ready-to-eat foods, instant mixes cut to 8 per cent

 Duty on footwear with a retail sale price between Rs 250 and Rs750 down to 8 per cent 

 Concessional 8 per cent rate for all LPG stoves 

 Duty on compact fluorescent lamps cut to 8 per cent from 16 per cent

 Glassware to attract 16 per cent duty on a par with 

 ceramicware and plasticware

 Duty on specified printing, writing and packing paper cut to 12 per cent from 16 per cent

 Cess on domestic crude up to Rs 2,500 per tonne

 12 per cent duty on computers reimposed

 Levy of 16 per cent on set-top boxes

 Duty on cigarettes up 5 per cent

 Customs

 Countervailing duty of 4 per cent on all imports

 Peak rate on non-farm products cut to 12.5 per cent from 15 per cent

 Duty on alloy steel and primary and secondary non-ferrous metals cut to 7.5 per cent from 10 per cent. Same rate of duty for ferro alloys

 Duty on steel melting scrap restored to 5 per cent; on a par with primary steel

 Duty on mineral products cut to 5 per cent from 15 per cent. Duty on ores and concentrates down to 2 per cent

 Duty on vanaspati up to 80 per cent

 Refractories to attract a duty of 7.5 per cent 

 Duty on basic inorganic chemicals cut to 10 per cent from 15 per cent 

 Duty on major bulk plastics down to 5 per cent from 10 per cent; duty on naphtha for plastics cut to nil

 Duty relief for AIDS, cancer and some life-saving drugs

 Duty on packaging machines cut to 5 per cent from 15 per cent

 Duty on man-made fibres, yarns cut to 10 per cent from 15 per cent

 Service tax

 Raised from 10 per cent to 12 per cent

 New services brought under tax net include:

 ATM operations, maintenance and management; 

 Registrars, share transfer agents and bankers to an issue; 

 Sale of space or time, other than in print media, for ads; event sponsorships, other than sports events, by 

 companies; 

 International air travel, excluding economy class; 

 Container services on rail, excluding freight charges; 

 Business support services; auctioneering; recovery agents; 

 Ship management services; travel on cruise ships; 

 Public relations management services

 Leasing and hire purchase industry gets relief

 April 1, 2010, date set for introducing GST




